item.title: UK probes kids syndrome, COVID-19 link
item.description: Some children in the United Kingdom with no underlying health conditions have died from a rare inflammatory syndrome which researchers believe to be linked to COVID-19, Health Secretary Matt Hancock says.

item.title: Another day, another plunge in world oil
item.description: Another big fall in oil prices has dragged hordes of petrocurrencies under but even an HSBC warning of mounting bad credit and a near 80 per cent plunge in BP's profits has not kept stock markets down for long.

item.title: Protester shot dead in unrest in Lebanon
item.description: A protester has been shot dead during unrest in the Lebanese city of Tripoli, security and medical sources have revealed, with an economic crisis bringing demonstrations back onto the streets.

item.title: Govt rejects China stance on virus review
item.description: The Morrison government has declared it won't give in to coercion as the Chinese embassy doubled down on its claims Australia's call for an investigation into the coronavirus is politically motivated and labelled our top diplomat a sham.

item.title: GM crops ban set to go in South Australia
item.description: A ban on genetically modified crops on the South Australian mainland is set to be scrapped with the Liberal government and the Labor opposition reaching a deal on proposed new laws.

item.title: Latest snapshot of the coronavirus impact
Jatinegara market Jakarta
item.description: Monkeys, monitors, bats, snakes, chickens all piled up on top of each other in cages in market.

item.title: Serious crash in Victoria’s southeast
item.description: A man and woman have been airlifted to Melbourne hospitals after their cars collided on an a freeway at Victoria's West Gippsland.

item.title: Virus economic hit worse than Depression
item.description: Businesses and jobs will be lost permanently because of the coronavirus crisis, which has caused a much faster economic shock than the Great Depression.

item.title: Maccas mayhem as New Zealand ends lockdown
item.description: New Zealanders eager for their first taste of McDonalds in more than a month have lined up before dawn in drive-through lanes as Kiwis celebrate the end of their brutal lockdown.
